# Why Metrics Are Essential in Business

When entrepreneurs appear on the Shark Tank TV show to pitch their company or product, the investors invariably ask them a few critical questions:

1. What’s your cost of customer acquisition?  
2. What’s your revenue?  
3. What’s your profit?

With surprisingly frequency, entrepreneurs are blindsided by these questions and either give off-the-cuff answers or fail to answer at all.

Of course, it makes sense why an investor would care. But as a business owner, why is it critical to keep an eagle-eye on your metrics?

## Your Instincts Lie

Your instinct is a great tool for navigating uncertainty. It’s particularly critical in the beginning stages of a new company that’s full of unknowns. However, as your business matures, relying strictly on instinct to make your decisions becomes increasingly dangerous.

For example:

* It’s easy to assume the part of your business with the most revenue or the most activity also generates the most net profit.

* It’s easy to overlook the individual who says little about the work she does, assuming she contributes only partially to a department’s success.

* It’s easy to assume a particular market is a great opportunity to pursue, given success in similar arenas.

Unfortunately, these assumptions are easily swayed by personal preference or past experiences. Whenever possible, it’s essential to measure these assumptions against hard facts. As your business grows, you cannot leave your decisions merely to instinct.

Let me explain.

## Your Averages Lie

Many great writers have brought awareness to the *Pareto Principle*, which can be simplified to this simple reality: *The majority of the outcomes are dictated by a small number of factors.*

This means just a few of your employees contribute the most to the productivity of your business or quality of the culture.

It means just a few of your services provide the greatest amount of satisfaction to your clients.

It means just a few of your products provide the greatest profitability.

Simply eliminating the unprofitable parts of your business often significantly improves the bottom line. However, that’s only possible when you specifically measure these components.

## Your Metrics Anchor You to Reality

Running your business with an eye on your metrics is the difference between flying a plane by mere sight or by the instruments. When you can define and measure your metrics, you can continue to keep your business aright amidst your ups and downs.

According to Lord Kelvin (and as popularized by Peter Drucker), you can only improve the things you measure. Your key metrics allow you to systematically continue improving your business, giving you an instant pulse for the health of your business.

If you can instantly identify a decline in new leads, you can take proactive steps in finding new leads before you hit a cash flow crisis.

This is precisely the purpose of custom software solutions. Not only can you identify problems before they grow, you can have these metrics *delivered to you* on a consistent basis. As you continue to scale your business, this allows you to focus on the essentials of your leadership while staying in touch with the direction of your organization.
